{{hatnote|Not to be confused with [[Michel Lazard]], another French mathematician.}}
{{BLP sources|date=December 2011}}
'''Daniel Lazard''' (born December 10, 1941) is a French mathematician and computer scientist. He is emeritus professor at [[Université Pierre et Marie Curie]].{{cn|date=August 2017}}

Lazard was born in [[Carpentras]]. He began his academic career by working in [[commutative algebra]], especially on [[flat module]]s.  Around 1970, he began to work in [[computer algebra]], which, soon after, became his main research area. In this field, he is specially interested in [[multivariate polynomial]]s and more generally in [[algebraic geometry#Computational algebraic geometry|computational algebraic geometry]], with emphasis on [[systems of polynomial equations|polynomial system solving]].{{cn|date=August 2017}}

D. Lazard retired from the Université Pierre et Marie Curie Paris 6 UFR in 2008. <ref>https://ac.els-cdn.com/S0747717108001090/1-s2.0-S0747717108001090-main.pdf?_tid=432ac271-f018-4959-b17a-a56d24fecb96&acdnat=1540752648_2b667a61e5a57bb42441a6bee8e0d4e8</ref>

==Selected  contributions==
* {{harvtxt|Lazard|1969}} noted that a module M is flat if and only if it is a direct limit of finitely-generated free modules. As a consequence, one can deduce that every finitely-presented flat module is projective. (See [[flat module#Categorical colimits]])
* In computer algebra, the [[resultant]] of two polynomials can be used to analyze modular images of the greatest common divisor of integer polynomials where the coefficients are taken modulo some prime number ''p''. The resultant of two polynomials is frequently computed in the Lazard-Rioboo-Trager method of finding the integral of a ratio of polynomials.
* {{harvtxt|Lazard|1992}} introduced the ''lextriangular algorithm'' to obtain the [[triangular decomposition]] of a polynomial system.  See [[System of polynomial equations#Regular chains]].

