'''Francis Sowerby Macaulay''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]<ref name="frs">{{Cite journal | last1 = Baker | first1 = H. F. | title = Francis Sowerby Macaulay. 1862-1937 | doi = 10.1098/rsbm.1938.0018 | journal = [[Obituary Notices of Fellows of the Royal Society]] | volume = 2 | issue = 6 | pages = 356–361| year = 1938 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref> (11 February 1862, [[Witney]] – 9 February 1937, [[Cambridge]]) was an [[England|English]] mathematician who made significant contributions to [[algebraic geometry]].<ref>{{MacTutor Biography|id=Macaulay}}</ref> He is known for his 1916 book ''The Algebraic Theory of Modular Systems'' (an old term for [[Ideal (ring theory)|ideals]]), which greatly influenced the later course of commutative algebra. [[Cohen–Macaulay ring]]s, [[Macaulay duality]], the [[Macaulay resultant]] and the [[Macaulay computer algebra system|Macaulay]] and [[Macaulay2]] computer algebra systems are named for Macaulay.

Macaulay was educated at [[Kingswood School]] and graduated with distinction from [[St John's College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=FML879FS|name=Macaulay, Francis Sowerby}}</ref> He taught top mathematics class in [[St Paul's School (London)|St Paul's School]] in [[London]] from 1885 to 1911.  His students included [[John Edensor Littlewood|J. E. Littlewood]] and [[G. N. Watson]].

In 1928 Macaulay was elected [[Fellow of the Royal Society]].<ref name="frs"/>

