{{nihongo|'''Takashi Ono'''|小野 孝|Ono Takashi|born 18 December 1928}} is a retired [[Japan]]ese-born [[American people|American]] mathematician, specializing in number theory and algebraic groups.

==Early life and education==
Takashi Ono was born in [[Nishinomiya]], [[Japan]]. He received his Ph.D. in 1958 at [[Nagoya University]].<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=85974}}</ref>

==Career==
Ono immigrated to the United States after receiving an invitation from [[J. Robert Oppenheimer]] to work at the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] with a fellowship for the two academic years 1959–1961<ref name="IASRef">{{cite web| url= http://www.ias.edu/people/cos/users/5385 |title= Ono, Takashi |publisher= [[Institute for Advanced Study]]| website= IAS.edu| date= | access-date= }}</ref> and then went to the [[University of British Columbia]] to work as a mathematics professor from 1961 to 1964.  

From 1964 to 1969 Ono was a tenured professor at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. From 1969 to his retirement in 2011, he was a professor at [[Johns Hopkins University]]. 

In 1966 he was an [[list of International Congresses of Mathematicians Plenary and Invited Speakers|invited speaker at the International Congress of Mathematicians]] in [[Moscow]].<ref name=IASRef/> In 2012 he was elected a Fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://hub.jhu.edu/2012/11/02/math-fellows-ams |title= 10 from JHU among inaugural fellows of American Mathematical Society| website= JHU.edu| publisher= [[Johns Hopkins University]]| date= | access-date= }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Ono's youngest son, [[Ken Ono]], is also a mathematician<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/wisconsin/29298744.html| deadurl= yes |title= A flash of insight brings answers|last= Johnson| first= Mike| newspaper= [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] |date=13 March 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111112195129/http://www.jsonline.com/news/wisconsin/29298744.html| archivedate= November 12, 2011| access-date= August 24, 2017}}</ref> and professor at [[Emory University]] as well as a former triathlete.<ref name= "Emory Ken">{{cite web| url= http://www.mathcs.emory.edu/~ono/about-me/| publisher= Department of Mathematics, [[Emory University]]| website= Emory.edu| title= About Me| first= Ken | last= Ono| access-date= August 24, 2017}}</ref> His middle son, [[Santa J. Ono]], is the President and Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of British Columbia]] (previously, the 28th President of the [[University of Cincinnati]]) and a biomedical researcher. His eldest son, Momoro Ono, is a music professor at [[Creighton University]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.creighton.edu/ccas/fineandperformingarts/degrees/music/musicfaculty/momoroono/ |title= Dr. Momoro Ono| publisher= Fine and Performing Arts, [[Creighton University]]| date= | access-date= August 24, 2017 | website= Creighton.edu}}</ref>

