'''Vadim V. Schechtman''' (Вадим Шехтман, born 8 June 1954) is a Russian mathematician who teaches in [[Toulouse]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.univ-toulouse.fr/~schechtman/|title=Vadim Schechtman|website=math.univ-toulouse.fr}}</ref>

Schechtman received in 1979 from [[Moscow State University]] his doctorate under the supervision of [[Evgeny Golod]].<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=73319}}</ref> Schechtman was an academic at Moscow State University in the 1980s and at [[Stony Brook University]] in the 1990s. He is a now a professor at [[Paul Sabatier University]] (Toulouse III).

His research deals with algebraic geometry and quantum groups as well as with mathematical physics.

He has collaborated with [[Alexander Varchenko]] and [[Alexander Beilinson]], among others.

Schechtman was an Invited Speaker with talk ''Sur les algèbres vertex attachées aux variétés algébriques'' at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] in Beijing in 2002.<ref>{{cite book|author=Schechtman, Vadim|chapter=Sur les algèbres vertex attachées aux variétés algébriques|title=Proceedings of the ICM, Beijing, 2002|year=2002|volume=vol. 2|pages=523–532}}</ref>

