'''Carlos Tschudi Simpson''' (born 30 June 1962) is an American mathematician, specializing in algebraic geometry.

Simpson received his [[Ph.D.]] in 1987 from [[Harvard University]], where he was supervised by [[Wilfried Schmid]]; his thesis was titled ''Systems of Hodge Bundles and Uniformization''.<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=44606}}</ref> He became a professor{{clarify|date=April 2016}} at the University of Toulouse III ([[Paul Sabatier University]]) and then at the [[University of Nice]]. He is research director of the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]].

He works on moduli spaces of [[vector bundle]]s, higher non-abelian [[de Rham cohomology]] ([[Hodge theory]]), the theory of [[Higher category theory|higher categories]] and computer verification of mathematical proofs (''e.g.'' verification of proofs within [[Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory]] using [[Coq]]). In his Ph.D. dissertation, Simpson studied the notion of system of [[Hodge bundle]]s, which can be seen as a special case of the higher dimensional generalization of [[Higgs bundle]]s introduced earlier by [[Nigel Hitchin]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ams.org/notices/200708/tx070800980p.pdf|first1= Steven B. | last1=Bradlow|first2= Oscar|last2= García-Prada|first3= Peter B. |last3= Gothen |title=What is a Higgs bundle ?|journal=[[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]]|volume= 54|year= 2007|pages= 980–981}}</ref>

The Deligne–Simpson Problem, an algebraic problem associated with [[Monodromy matrix|monodromy matrices]], is named after Carlos Simpson and [[Pierre Deligne]].<ref>{{cite journal|arxiv=math/0206298|first= Vladimir Petrov|last=Kostov |title=The Deligne-Simpson problem—a survey|year=2004|journal=[[Journal of Algebra]]|issue=1|pages=83–108|mr=2091962|doi=10.1016/j.jalgebra.2004.07.013}}</ref>

Simpson was an Invited Speaker with talk ''Nonabelian Hodge theory'' at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] in 1990 at [[Kyoto]]. In 2015 he received the [[Sophie Germain Prize]].

