'''Charles Herschel Sisam''' (8 September 1879, [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]] – 4 December 1964) was an American mathematician.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.coloradocollege.edu/academics/dept/mathematics/timeline/faculty/Sisam.html |title=Professor Charles Sisam • Mathematics & Computer Science, Colorado College |access-date=2016-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405215050/https://www.coloradocollege.edu/academics/dept/mathematics/timeline/faculty/Sisam.html |archive-date=2018-04-05 |dead-url=yes }}</ref><ref>[https://www.math.cornell.edu/m/node/6952 Cornell Mathematics Sesquicentenial Historical Notes. Chapter II: 1895–1925 | www.math.cornell.edu]</ref>

He received his B.A. in 1902 from the [[University of Michigan]] and then his M.A. in 1903 and Ph.D. in 1906, under the supervision of [[Virgil Snyder]], from [[Cornell University]].<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=9295}}</ref> While working on his Ph.D., Sisam was a mathematics instructor at the [[United States Naval Academy]] from 1904 to 1906.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Sisam, Charles H(erschel)|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J9sSAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA293|title=American Men of Science: A Biographical Directory|year=1906|page=293}}</ref> He was an instructor in 1906–1907, a research associate in 1907–1909, and an assistant professor in 1909–1918 at the University of Illinois. From 1918 to 1948 he was a full professor at [[Colorado College]]. He did research on algebraic surfaces and was an Invited Speaker at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians|ICM]] in 1928 in Bologna.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sisam, C. H.|title=On ruled three-dimensional varieties of order five|journal=Atti del Congresso Internazionale dei Matematici: Bologna del 3 al 10 de settembre di 1928|pages=193–194|year=1929|url=http://www.mathunion.org/ICM/ICM1928.4/Main/icm1928.4.0193.0194.ocr.pdf|access-date=2016-06-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924200349/http://www.mathunion.org/ICM/ICM1928.4/Main/icm1928.4.0193.0194.ocr.pdf#|archive-date=2016-09-24|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> He was on the editorial staff of the [[Transactions of the American Mathematical Society]] from 1930 to 1936.

Sisam married and was the father of a daughter.

